\title{CleanTest-Agent: A Multi-Agent Skill-Orchestrated System for \\ Unit Test Training Data Quality Assurance}

\author{[Your Name]}
\affiliation{
  \institution{Beihang University}
  \department{School of Software}
  \city{Beijing}
  \country{China}
}
\email{[your-email]@buaa.edu.cn}

\begin{abstract}
The quality of training data significantly impacts the performance of AI-based unit test generation models. Recent studies have shown that up to 43.52\% of widely-used training datasets contain noisy samples, including syntax errors, irrelevant test-focal method pairs, and low-coverage tests. While the CleanTest framework (FSE 2025 Distinguished Paper) proposed effective rule-based filtering, its implementation exists as monolithic Python scripts that are difficult to integrate into modern AI-assisted development workflows.

In this paper, we present \textbf{CleanTest-Agent}, a multi-agent skill-orchestrated system that transforms the CleanTest data cleaning pipeline into composable, reusable \textit{Agent Skills} compatible with coding assistants such as CodeBuddy, Claude Code, and Cursor. Our system employs a three-stage pipeline: (1)~a syntax noise filter using tree-sitter AST parsing with Aho-Corasick multi-pattern matching, (2)~a relevance filter combining AST-based method name matching with LLM semantic judgment for borderline cases, and (3)~a coverage prediction filter using a fine-tuned GPT-2 regression model.

We evaluate CleanTest-Agent on the full Methods2Test dataset (593,953 samples) and compare four approaches: rule-based only, pure LLM zero-shot, pure LLM few-shot, and our hybrid method. Results show that our system achieves an F1 score of 0.9651 while the best pure LLM approach (few-shot) only achieves 0.7894. Furthermore, our hybrid approach costs only \$0.01 per 500 samples compared to \$0.25 for the few-shot baseline --- a 25$\times$ cost reduction. The full pipeline processes 593,953 samples in under 3 minutes with Aho-Corasick optimization (11.5$\times$ speedup over na\"ive string matching). These results demonstrate that systematic software design --- combining rule-based analysis with selective LLM enhancement --- outperforms pure LLM approaches in specialized code analysis tasks.
\end{abstract}

\keywords{unit test generation, data quality, multi-agent systems, code analysis, LLM, software engineering}

\maketitle

% ============================================================================
\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:introduction}
% ============================================================================

The advent of large language models (LLMs) has revolutionized automated unit test generation, with models such as CodeBERT~\cite{feng2020codebert}, CodeT5~\cite{wang2021codet5}, StarCoder~\cite{li2023starcoder}, and CodeLlama~\cite{roziere2023code} demonstrating remarkable capabilities in generating test cases from focal methods. These models are typically fine-tuned on large-scale datasets like Methods2Test~\cite{tufano2022methods2test} and ATLAS~\cite{watson2020atlas}, which contain hundreds of thousands of focal method--test case pairs extracted from open-source Java projects.

However, the quality of these training datasets has been largely overlooked. Zhang et al.~\cite{zhang2025cleantest} recently conducted a comprehensive study revealing that \textbf{43.52\% of the Methods2Test dataset contains noisy samples} --- a finding that earned the FSE 2025 Distinguished Paper Award. These noise types include syntax errors, empty exception handlers, empty method bodies, ambiguous generic types, unnecessary Java annotations, non-English literals, and test cases that are semantically irrelevant to their paired focal methods. Training on such noisy data degrades model performance across all evaluation metrics.

The CleanTest framework proposed by Zhang et al. provides an effective three-filter pipeline: a rule-based syntax filter, a relevance filter, and a GPT-2-based coverage prediction filter. However, the original implementation exists as standalone Python scripts that are tightly coupled to specific file paths and data formats. This monolithic design presents several challenges:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Poor reusability}: The scripts cannot be easily invoked by AI coding assistants or integrated into automated workflows.
    \item \textbf{Limited extensibility}: Adding new noise types requires modifying core scripts rather than composing new modules.
    \item \textbf{No interactive feedback}: Users cannot inspect intermediate results or adjust filtering thresholds during execution.
    \item \textbf{Performance bottlenecks}: The original annotation matching uses linear scan over 21,954 patterns, making it prohibitively slow for large datasets.
\end{enumerate}

In this paper, we present \textbf{CleanTest-Agent}, a system that addresses these challenges through a multi-agent skill-orchestrated architecture. Our key contributions are:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Skill-based architecture}: We decompose the CleanTest pipeline into four composable Agent Skills (pipeline orchestrator, syntax filter, relevance filter, coverage filter), each following the standard \texttt{SKILL.md} protocol compatible with multiple coding assistants.

    \item \textbf{Hybrid rule-LLM approach}: We enhance the rule-based filters with selective LLM consultation for borderline cases, achieving higher accuracy while keeping costs minimal (only $\sim$12.7\% of samples require LLM calls).

    \item \textbf{Aho-Corasick optimization}: We replace the na\"ive linear annotation matching with an Aho-Corasick automaton, achieving an \textbf{11.5$\times$ speedup} (30 minutes $\to$ 2.6 minutes on 593,953 samples).

    \item \textbf{Comprehensive evaluation}: We compare four approaches (rule-based, zero-shot LLM, few-shot LLM, hybrid) and demonstrate that our hybrid approach achieves the best F1 (0.9651) at the lowest cost (\$0.01/500 samples).
\end{enumerate}

The remainder of this paper is organized as follows. Section~\ref{sec:background} reviews related work. Section~\ref{sec:requirements} presents the requirements analysis. Section~\ref{sec:design} describes the system design. Section~\ref{sec:implementation} details the implementation. Section~\ref{sec:evaluation} presents the experimental evaluation. Section~\ref{sec:discussion} discusses the findings, and Section~\ref{sec:conclusion} concludes the paper.


% ============================================================================
\section{Background and Related Work}
\label{sec:background}
% ============================================================================

\subsection{Unit Test Generation}

Automated unit test generation has been an active research area in software engineering. Traditional approaches include search-based methods like EvoSuite~\cite{fraser2011evosuite}, random testing tools like Randoop~\cite{pacheco2007randoop}, and symbolic execution-based methods. More recently, neural approaches have gained prominence:

\textbf{Methods2Test}~\cite{tufano2022methods2test} introduced a large-scale dataset of 780K Java focal method--test case pairs and demonstrated that transformer models can learn to generate meaningful test cases. \textbf{ATLAS}~\cite{watson2020atlas} provided an assertion-level dataset for test oracle generation.

\textbf{A3Test}~\cite{alagarsamy2023a3test} used domain adaptation techniques to improve test generation. \textbf{ChatUniTest}~\cite{chen2024chatunitest} leveraged ChatGPT with adaptive focal context for test generation.

\subsection{Data Quality in Software Engineering}

The impact of data quality on machine learning for software engineering has been studied in several contexts. Allamanis~\cite{allamanis2019adverse} showed that code duplication in training data leads to inflated performance estimates. Tu et al.~\cite{tu2014localness} demonstrated that code naturalness varies significantly across projects.

\textbf{CleanTest}~\cite{zhang2025cleantest} is the most directly related work. Zhang et al. conducted a systematic study of noise in unit test training data, identifying seven categories of syntactic noise plus relevance and coverage-based noise. They proposed a three-filter pipeline and showed that training on cleaned data (``less is more'') consistently improves model performance across CodeBERT, CodeT5, StarCoder, and CodeLlama. Their work received the FSE 2025 Distinguished Paper Award.

Our work builds upon CleanTest by transforming its pipeline into a modular, extensible agent skill architecture while introducing LLM enhancement and algorithmic optimization.

\subsection{LLM-Based Code Analysis}

Large language models have been increasingly applied to code analysis tasks. GPT-4~\cite{openai2023gpt4} and Claude~\cite{anthropic2024claude} can perform zero-shot code review, bug detection, and quality assessment. However, several studies have highlighted limitations:

Zhao et al.~\cite{zhao2026citation} demonstrated that LLMs exhibit citation hallucination in academic contexts. PaperOrchestra~\cite{song2026paperorchestra} showed that multi-agent systems with Semantic Scholar API verification significantly outperform single-agent approaches for literature review.

In the code domain, LLMs struggle with precise pattern matching tasks that require knowledge of large dictionaries (e.g., 21,954 annotation patterns). Our hybrid approach addresses this by using deterministic rules for pattern matching while leveraging LLM capabilities for semantic understanding.

\subsection{Agent Skill Architectures}

The concept of composable agent skills has gained traction with the rise of AI coding assistants. \textbf{Superpowers}~\cite{vincent2026superpowers} introduced a skills framework and software development methodology for Claude Code, emphasizing test-driven development and systematic debugging.

\textbf{Academic Research Skills (ARS)}~\cite{wu2026ars} demonstrated how multi-agent skill pipelines can orchestrate complex academic workflows. Both frameworks use the \texttt{SKILL.md} protocol, where each skill is defined by a Markdown file containing trigger phrases, workflow instructions, and references.

Our work adapts this protocol for the data quality domain, demonstrating that the skill-based architecture is applicable beyond coding and writing tasks.


% ============================================================================
\section{Requirements Analysis}
\label{sec:requirements}
% ============================================================================

\subsection{Problem Statement}

Given a unit test training dataset $D = \{(f_i, t_i)\}_{i=1}^{N}$ where $f_i$ is a focal method and $t_i$ is a test case, the goal is to identify and remove noisy samples that would degrade the performance of test generation models trained on $D$.

\subsection{Use Cases}

We identify three primary use cases:

\textbf{UC1: Batch Dataset Cleaning.} A researcher preparing a training dataset invokes the pipeline on a CSV file containing focal method--test case pairs. The system processes all samples through three filter stages and outputs a cleaned dataset with a noise report.

\textbf{UC2: Interactive Noise Inspection.} A developer using a coding assistant (e.g., CodeBuddy) asks ``check if this test is noisy'' for individual samples. The system invokes the appropriate filter skill and provides a diagnosis with confidence.

\textbf{UC3: Incremental Filter Extension.} A researcher wants to add a new noise type (e.g., flaky test detection). They create a new skill directory with a \texttt{SKILL.md} and register it with the pipeline orchestrator without modifying existing code.

