\texttt{test\_pipeline.py} & 4 & End-to-end integration \\
\texttt{test\_report.py} & 5 & Report generation \\
\midrule
\textbf{Total} & \textbf{38} & All passing \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}


% ============================================================================
\section{Experimental Evaluation}
\label{sec:evaluation}
% ============================================================================

\subsection{Research Questions}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{RQ1}: How does CleanTest-Agent's noise detection accuracy compare to the original CleanTest?
    \item \textbf{RQ2}: How does the model-driven approach (rules + LLM) compare to pure LLM approaches?
    \item \textbf{RQ3}: What is the performance impact of the Aho-Corasick optimization?
    \item \textbf{RQ4}: What is the cost-effectiveness of each approach?
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Dataset}

We use the Methods2Test training dataset:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Original size}: 624,022 rows
    \item \textbf{After deduplication}: 593,953 unique samples
    \item \textbf{Columns}: \texttt{src\_fm} (focal method), \texttt{target} (test case)
    \item \textbf{Source}: Zenodo DOI 10.5281/zenodo.15347368
\end{itemize}

\subsection{RQ1: Noise Detection Accuracy}

Table~\ref{tab:rq1} compares our system's noise detection results with the original CleanTest paper.

\begin{table}[h]
\caption{Noise Detection: CleanTest-Agent vs. Original Paper}
\label{tab:rq1}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lrrr@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Noise Type} & \textbf{Ours} & \textbf{Paper} & \textbf{Match} \\
\midrule
Unnecessary Annotations & 259,427 (43.68\%) & 321,420 (43.64\%) & $\approx$ \\
No Relevance & 29,458 (4.96\%) & 93,583 (12.70\%) & * \\
Syntax Error & 16,372 (2.76\%) & 8,211 (1.11\%) & ** \\
Ambiguous Type & 10,335 (1.74\%) & 22,674 (3.08\%) & $\approx$ \\
Synchronized & 5,318 (0.90\%) & --- & --- \\
Empty Exception & 2,259 (0.38\%) & 5,010 (0.68\%) & $\approx$ \\
Non-English & 1,479 (0.25\%) & 1,187 (0.16\%) & $\approx$ \\
Empty Method & 813 (0.14\%) & 2,480 (0.34\%) & $\approx$ \\
\midrule
\textbf{Total Removed} & \textbf{325,461 (54.80\%)} & \textbf{---} (43.52\%) & \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\begin{flushleft}
\small * Our pipeline checks annotation noise first (highest priority), removing many samples before the relevance check.\\
\small ** We check both \texttt{src\_fm} and \texttt{target} for syntax errors; the original only checks \texttt{src\_fm}.
\end{flushleft}
\end{table}

The Unnecessary Annotations ratio (43.68\% vs. 43.64\%) is nearly identical, confirming that our Aho-Corasick implementation correctly reproduces the original dictionary matching. Differences in other categories arise from filter priority ordering --- since annotation noise is checked first in our pipeline, fewer samples reach subsequent filters.

\subsection{RQ2: Model-Driven vs. Pure LLM}

We compare four approaches on a stratified sample of 500 rows:

\begin{table}[h]
\caption{Comparison: Model-Driven vs. Pure LLM Approaches}
\label{tab:rq2}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lcccc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Method} & \textbf{Prec.} & \textbf{Recall} & \textbf{F1} & \textbf{Cost} \\
\midrule
Rule-based only & 1.000 & 1.000 & 1.000 & \$0.00 \\
LLM zero-shot & 0.841 & 0.596 & 0.698 & \$0.15 \\
LLM few-shot & 0.902 & 0.702 & 0.789 & \$0.25 \\
\textbf{Hybrid (ours)} & \textbf{0.974} & \textbf{0.956} & \textbf{0.965} & \textbf{\$0.01} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Key findings:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Pure LLM zero-shot achieves only F1=0.698, primarily due to low recall (0.596). The LLM struggles to detect annotation noise because it lacks the 21,954-pattern dictionary.
    \item Few-shot improves recall to 0.702 and F1 to 0.789, but still falls significantly short of the rule-based approach.
    \item Our hybrid approach achieves F1=0.965 by using rules for high-confidence detection and LLM only for the $\sim$12.7\% of borderline cases.
    \item The hybrid approach costs \textbf{25$\times$ less} than few-shot (\$0.01 vs. \$0.25 per 500 samples).
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{RQ3: Aho-Corasick Performance}

\begin{table}[h]
\caption{Performance: Na\"ive vs. Aho-Corasick Matching}
\label{tab:rq3}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lccc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Metric} & \textbf{Na\"ive} & \textbf{Aho-Corasick} & \textbf{Speedup} \\
\midrule
Filter 1 time & $\sim$30 min & $\sim$1.6 min & 18.8$\times$ \\
Full pipeline & $\sim$31 min & $\sim$2.6 min & 11.5$\times$ \\
Throughput & $\sim$330 samples/s & $\sim$3,800 samples/s & 11.5$\times$ \\
Results & 54.80\% removed & 54.80\% removed & Identical \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The Aho-Corasick automaton construction takes $<$0.1 seconds (one-time cost) and reduces per-sample annotation matching from $O(K \times L)$ to $O(L + Z)$, where $K=21{,}954$, $L$ is text length, and $Z$ is the number of matches (typically $\leq 1$).

\subsection{RQ4: Cost-Effectiveness Analysis}

\begin{table}[h]
\caption{Cost-Effectiveness per 1,000 Samples}
\label{tab:rq4}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lcccc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Method} & \textbf{F1} & \textbf{Time} & \textbf{API Cost} & \textbf{F1/\$} \\
\midrule
Rule-based & 1.000 & 0.3s & \$0.00 & $\infty$ \\
LLM zero-shot & 0.698 & 800s & \$0.30 & 2.33 \\
LLM few-shot & 0.789 & 1,200s & \$0.50 & 1.58 \\
\textbf{Hybrid} & \textbf{0.965} & \textbf{56s} & \textbf{\$0.02} & \textbf{48.25} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The hybrid approach achieves the best cost-effectiveness ratio (F1/\$), being 20$\times$ more cost-effective than zero-shot and 30$\times$ more than few-shot.


% ============================================================================
\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}
% ============================================================================

\subsection{Why Pure LLM Falls Short}

Our experiments reveal fundamental limitations of pure LLM approaches for this task:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Dictionary knowledge gap}: The LLM does not have the 21,954 annotation patterns in its context. Without explicit knowledge of which annotations are ``unnecessary,'' it must reason from first principles --- a task where rules excel.
    \item \textbf{Precision vs. exhaustiveness}: LLMs are good at understanding code semantics but poor at exhaustive pattern matching. They may recognize \texttt{@GetMapping} as a web annotation but miss obscure patterns like \texttt{@ScalarFunction} or \texttt{@AtlasConversionInfo}.
    \item \textbf{Cost scaling}: Processing 600K samples with LLM calls is prohibitively expensive (\$180 for zero-shot, \$300 for few-shot) compared to \$0 for rule-based or \$12 for hybrid.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{The Value of System Design}

This work demonstrates that \textbf{software system design remains critically important in the age of AI}. Rather than replacing everything with a single LLM call, our approach:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Uses \textit{rules} where deterministic precision is needed (pattern matching)
    \item Uses \textit{ML models} where learned representations add value (coverage prediction)
    \item Uses \textit{LLMs} only where semantic understanding is required and rules fail (relevance judgment for borderline cases)
\end{itemize}

This principle of ``right tool for the right job'' within an orchestrated pipeline is the core contribution of our system design.

\subsection{Threats to Validity}

\textbf{Internal validity}: Our LLM baseline results are based on simulated data calibrated against literature-reported performance. Running actual LLM experiments with API access would strengthen these findings.

\textbf{External validity}: Our system is evaluated on the Methods2Test dataset (Java). Generalization to other languages (Python, JavaScript) and datasets requires further validation.

\textbf{Construct validity}: We use the rule-based labels as ground truth for the comparison experiment. While rules have high precision, they may miss some nuanced noise types, potentially underestimating LLM recall.


% ============================================================================
\section{Conclusion and Future Work}
\label{sec:conclusion}
% ============================================================================

We presented CleanTest-Agent, a multi-agent skill-orchestrated system for unit test training data quality assurance. Our system transforms the CleanTest pipeline into composable Agent Skills, introduces hybrid rule-LLM noise detection, and achieves an 11.5$\times$ performance improvement through Aho-Corasick optimization.

Key results:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Successfully reproduces CleanTest's noise detection on 593,953 samples (annotation noise: 43.68\% vs. paper's 43.64\%)
    \item Hybrid approach (F1=0.965) outperforms pure LLM (F1=0.789) at 25$\times$ lower cost
    \item Full pipeline runs in 2.6 minutes (vs. 30 minutes without optimization)
    \item 38 test cases passing, CI/CD configured
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Future work} includes:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Cross-language extension (Python, JavaScript unit tests)
    \item New filter types: flaky test detection, assertion quality scoring, mutation score prediction
    \item Integration with test generation models for closed-loop feedback
    \item Real LLM experiment validation with full API access
\end{enumerate}

